digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Potentiometer -> Buffer -> LowPassFilter -> GainStage -> AntiAliasingFilter -> DAQ;

    Potentiometer [label="Potentiometer\n(10 kOhms)"];
    Buffer [label="Buffer Amplifier"];
    LowPassFilter [label="Low-pass Filter\n(Notch at 50/60 Hz)"];
    GainStage [label="Gain Stage"];
    AntiAliasingFilter [label="Anti-aliasing Filter"];
    DAQ [label="Data Acquisition System\n(DAQ)"];
}
```

```Explanations
Potentiometer: This is a linear 10 kOhms potentiometer connected to the pendulum. As the pendulum swings, the potentiometer's wiper moves accordingly, producing a voltage proportional to the angle of the pendulum.

Buffer Amplifier: This block provides a high input impedance to avoid loading the potentiometer and a low output impedance to drive the subsequent stages. It ensures that the potentiometer's output voltage is not affected by the input impedance of the following stages.

Low-pass Filter (Notch at 50/60 Hz): The main function of this block is to filter out unwanted 50/60 Hz noise which could be introduced from power lines or electronic devices operating at these frequencies. This helps to ensure that the signal being fed to the DAQ is as clean as possible.

Gain Stage: The gain stage amplifies the signal to match the input voltage range of the DAQ. This stage adjusts the amplitude of the signal so that the full swing of the pendulum corresponds to the maximum voltage range that the DAQ can read.

Anti-aliasing Filter: Prior to digital acquisition, this filter removes high-frequency components from the signal to prevent aliasing when the analog signal is sampled by the DAQ. As a rule of thumb, this filter should have a cutoff frequency less than half of the DAQ's sampling rate (Nyquist frequency).

DAQ: The Data Acquisition System reads the analog signal and converts it into digital data for processing. The DAQ must have a sufficient sampling rate to accurately capture the signal provided by the anti-aliasing filter.
```

